article.description:
With a chance to extend their 
franchise-record home winning streak to six games, the Memphis
Grizzlies had the wrong opponent on the schedule.
article.headline: Mailman scores 17 points for Utah
article.linkText: Grizzlies home winning streak ends thanks to Jazz
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Utah Jazz didn't waste any time running away from the Memphis Grizzlies. Holding Memphis to 17 percent shooting and 11 points in the first quarter, Utah built a 37-point lead in the second half and coasted to a 103-74 victory Sunday afternoon. "We have beat these guys before, and we knew that a good start, a good quick start, would be in our favor,'' Jazz forward Matt Harpring said. "We came out and put pressure on them right away. They had to play catch-up from the tip-off.'' Harpring and Karl Malone scored 17 points each to lead the Jazz, snapping Memphis' five-game home winning streak. Utah has won two straight, both on the road, following a four-game losing streak. "I thought (Malone) was terrific defensively and gave us a nice start,'' Jazz guard John Stockton said. "Our guys responded around him. There were active hands, and there was good solid defense. That's the way we need to play.'' Andrei Kirilenko added 15 for Utah, and Tony Massenburg, who played last season in Memphis, scored 11. Malone also had 11 rebounds. Memphis did not have a player in double figures until Mike Batiste scored with 49 seconds remaining. Shane Battier finished with 11, while Batiste had 10. The Jazz also beat the Grizzlies easily on Dec. 6, winning at home 104-71. This one was over early as Utah built a 54-31 halftime lead. The Grizzlies shot 30 percent in the half and made just three baskets in 18 first-quarter attempts. They also had 20 turnovers. "Not only were we missing shots, but we were also turning the ball over,'' Memphis coach Hubie Brown said. "In both games, they shot over 50 percent, and we have shot in the 30s. We just couldn't get key people on track.'' Utah managed only 35 percent from the field and still led 21-11 after the first period. It was the Grizzlies' lowest-scoring quarter of the season. In the second, the Jazz pulled away by making 13 of their 15 shots. "Utah is the type of team when they get in a rhythm of making a lot of their shots, you can't stop them,'' Memphis guard Brevin Knight said. Harpring led the Jazz with 13 points, and Malone had 11 at the half on 5-of-6 shooting. Jazz coach Jerry Sloan, like the Utah players, credited the work on the defensive end with the quick start. "We were strong defensively, which made it work both ways for us,'' Sloan said. "We had 30 deflections in the first half, which was a pretty good indicator that we played well.'' By the end of the third, Utah extended the lead to 81-48, leading by as many as 35 in the period. "I think they had our concentration from the get-go,'' said Stockton, who had eight points and nine assists. "We played one of our better defensive games, which gave us a lift.''

Game notes
The Grizzlies also set a season-low for a half by scoring only 31 in the opening 24 minutes. ... Utah shot 41 free throws and made 32, season-highs against the Grizzlies in both categories. ... Memphis G Wesley Person left the game with a jammed finger in the third quarter and did not return. The injury will be evaluated Monday... When Sloan was asked if there seemed to be more fighting in the NBA this year, the Utah coach said: "It's a good thing they didn't play in the '60s. These guys fight each other with powder puffs. I didn't see a heck of a great deal of reaction in the fight Mills and Wells had. They held each other, and I thought they were going to kiss for a little bit.'' Sloan was considered one of the toughest NBA players during his career, making the league's all-defensive first team four times.
